 A female infant was admitted with a lethal intracerebral hemorrhage secondary to vitamin K deficiency although vitamin K prophylaxis had been given by mouth on three occasions during the neonatal period. Histological examination of the liver demonstrated cholestasis that could have caused the malabsorption of vitamin K given orally. This case report calls in question the efficacy of the oral regimen as actually practiced in Germany as against alternative methods of vitamin K prophylaxis.  
